      "pipelines/validation/ — champion/challenger comparison script",
      "pipelines/labeling/ — joins prediction logs with delivery outcomes",
      "infra/model-registry/ — S3 bucket config + Postgres metadata schema",
      "monitoring/dashboards/ — Grafana dashboard definitions for latency and prediction drift",
      "tests/integration/test_feature_parity.py — asserts training and serving compute identical features"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Treat the ML model as a versioned artifact, not code. The serving path is a conventional microservice that happens to load a model. Keep the training pipeline boring — batch SQL/Spark joins, standard scikit-learn/LightGBM fit, write artifact to S3. No exotic infrastructure. The Feature Store is a shared Python package, not a platform.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT call external APIs (weather, traffic) synchronously during inference — cache them with TTLs and refresh async",
      "DO NOT use a heavyweight ML platform (Kubeflow, SageMaker) for a 4-person team — the operational overhead will consume all capacity",
      "DO NOT skip the Validation Gate — automatically promoting every trained model will eventually ship a broken one",
      "DO NOT store features differently for training vs serving — this is the root of training-serving skew",
      "DO NOT use deep learning for V1 — tabular data with ~6 features is LightGBM territory; neural nets add latency, complexity, and GPU cost for negligible accuracy gain",
      "DO NOT log predictions synchronously — use an in-process buffer with async flush to avoid adding latency to the serving path"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 85,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "In-process LightGBM/XGBoost serving will meet 100ms P99 with massive headroom",
      "Champion/Challenger with manual rollback is the right V1 for a 4-person team",
      "Shared feature definitions between training and serving is non-negotiable",
